### Save State Protocol
When {{USER_NAME}} says "save my state", "save my progress", or similar — or at natural checkpoints (after completing an issue, before a commit, after a significant milestone) — write a structured state file to the project folder.

**File location:** `.copilot/session-state.md` in the project root (create `.copilot/` if it doesn't exist)

**File format:**
```markdown
# Session State — [Project Name]
Last updated: [ISO timestamp]
Instance: [work|personal]
Machine: [from instance-config.json instance_name]

## Active Session
- Session ID: [current session ID]
- Working directory: [cwd]
- Persona: [active persona name]

## Session History
| Session ID | Date | Summary |
|-----------|------|---------|
| [id] | [date] | [one-line summary] |

## Current Status
[2-3 sentences: what was just completed, what's in progress]

## In Progress
- [ ] [item with enough detail to resume without context]

## Completed This Session
- [x] [item]

## Next Steps
- [ ] [item — what to do when resuming]

## Open Issues Being Worked
| # | Title | Status |
|---|-------|--------|
| [number] | [title] | [in-progress/blocked/ready for UAT] |

## Uncommitted Changes
[list any files modified but not yet committed, or "None — all changes committed"]
```

**Behavior:**
- **Auto-save:** Write/update `.copilot/session-state.md` after completing an issue, after committing, or at other natural breakpoints
- **Manual save:** Write/update immediately when {{USER_NAME}} asks to save state
- **On resume:** When {{USER_NAME}} says "pick up where I left off", "resume my project", "continue my project", or similar — OR when opening a project for the first time in a session — check for `.copilot/session-state.md` and offer a summary: "Last session [date] on [machine]: [status]. Want to pick up where you left off?" Then read the state file to restore context.
- **Session history:** Append the current session to the Session History table (don't overwrite previous entries)
- **Git:** `.copilot/` in project folders should be gitignored (it's local working state, not repo content)
